WEBVTT

00:02.136 --> 00:04.205
<i>♪ MTV</i>

00:07.708 --> 00:09.476
[Cara]
<i>Don't kill yourself</i>

00:09.477 --> 00:11.044
racing back to me in a blizzard.

00:11.045 --> 00:12.979
[Jacob]
<i>I will not allow</i>

00:12.980 --> 00:15.916
today to be the last time
I see your face.

00:17.551 --> 00:19.353
I belong with my husband.

00:20.254 --> 00:22.556
You're pregnant?

00:23.924 --> 00:25.158
[indistinct chatter]

00:25.159 --> 00:26.659
- Why you go home?
- Family needs me.

00:26.660 --> 00:28.129
<i>They're in danger.</i>

00:29.197 --> 00:30.330
[overlapping shouting]

00:30.331 --> 00:33.466
I am looking
for a Crow Indian girl,

00:33.467 --> 00:34.935
<i>16 years old.</i>

00:36.304 --> 00:38.171
- Can I help you?
- [Darling] You're under arrest

00:38.172 --> 00:40.173
for violating Montana's statute
against miscegenation.

00:40.174 --> 00:41.741
- [exclaims]
- Hey!

00:41.742 --> 00:43.510
[Alice]
No, no!

00:43.511 --> 00:44.844
[sobbing]

00:44.845 --> 00:46.146
How much trouble are they in?

00:46.147 --> 00:47.514
Well, the marriage is void.

00:47.515 --> 00:49.182
It's that fucking Whitfield.

00:49.183 --> 00:52.152
<i>He's gonna knock all
your chess pieces off the board.</i>

00:52.153 --> 00:54.387
[Ellie] <i>When you lay down
with dogs, Banner,</i>

00:54.388 --> 00:56.189
you stand up with fleas.

00:56.190 --> 00:58.258
All our lives we've had nothing.

00:58.259 --> 01:00.761
Now we have something,
and it ain't fleas.

01:05.266 --> 01:07.200
<i>♪ slow, solemn music</i>

01:07.201 --> 01:09.569
<i>***</i>

01:09.570 --> 01:12.405
[Elsa] <i>Only fire has
a more disruptive effect</i>

01:12.406 --> 01:16.042
<i>upon the order of the forest
than a blizzard.</i>

01:16.043 --> 01:17.877
<i>Whole herds of cattle</i>

01:17.878 --> 01:21.548
<i>and buffalo and elk
will wander maddening circles</i>

01:21.549 --> 01:26.353
<i>until the snowdrifts cover them
and they are frozen in place.</i>

01:26.354 --> 01:30.590
<i>The blizzard drives man
and animal both mad with hunger</i>

01:30.591 --> 01:35.595
<i>and cold and the disorienting
nature of no sun or moon,</i>

01:35.596 --> 01:38.465
<i>which is to say no direction,</i>

01:38.466 --> 01:41.169
<i>no compass to guide movement
or reason.</i>

01:44.272 --> 01:47.175
You're not using the house.

01:50.344 --> 01:52.579
Better I'm with my family
in the winter.

01:52.580 --> 01:56.082
Logic would suggest
moving the family to town

01:56.083 --> 01:58.285
rather than you to the family

01:58.286 --> 02:02.690
in a sod house frozen with snow.

02:03.791 --> 02:05.258
I don't trust town.

02:05.259 --> 02:08.561
Don't trust that sheriff either.

02:08.562 --> 02:11.931
Sits too deep
in Dutton's pocket.

02:11.932 --> 02:15.035
I suppose someone must
watch after the flock.

02:15.969 --> 02:18.239
Too much folly
for a boy and a woman.

02:19.373 --> 02:21.209
Got no flock anymore.

02:22.210 --> 02:24.312
They got flukes.

02:26.347 --> 02:28.682
Killed them all.

02:29.650 --> 02:32.220
[laughing]

02:33.654 --> 02:36.789
Look at all you sacrificed

02:36.790 --> 02:38.758
and suffered

02:38.759 --> 02:41.329
to protect sheep.

02:42.363 --> 02:46.033
You killed men
and almost died yourself.

02:47.034 --> 02:49.469
And all it took was a worm

02:49.470 --> 02:52.505
to destroy everything
you fought for.

02:52.506 --> 02:55.775
Livestock isn't a business,
Banner.

02:55.776 --> 02:58.446
It's the toil of peasants.

02:59.480 --> 03:01.349
It should be left to them.

03:02.350 --> 03:05.253
You are no peasant. Not anymore.

03:08.522 --> 03:10.891
Snow should begin
melting next month.

03:12.693 --> 03:14.827
We'll dig another shaft.

03:14.828 --> 03:17.464
Worms...

03:17.465 --> 03:20.200
don't kill gold.

03:21.469 --> 03:24.304
It's immune to drought
and to winter,

03:24.305 --> 03:26.673
and its demand is endless.

03:26.674 --> 03:29.677
That is a business.

03:32.413 --> 03:34.114
Stop the car.

03:47.728 --> 03:50.130
What the hell are they doing?

03:53.334 --> 03:54.567
Some
of the Norwegian miners asked

03:54.568 --> 03:55.702
if they could ski the mountain.

03:55.703 --> 03:57.537
I didn't see the harm in it,

03:57.538 --> 03:59.406
at least not for us.

03:59.407 --> 04:01.341
I figured if they want
to kill themselves

04:01.342 --> 04:03.710
on the side of a mountain,
so be it.

04:03.711 --> 04:05.177
You must take me to them.

04:05.178 --> 04:08.348
Now!

04:08.349 --> 04:10.550
Banner, hurry!

04:10.551 --> 04:12.051
I don't see the hurry.

04:12.052 --> 04:14.454
It's just a bunch
of drunk blokes teasing death.

04:14.455 --> 04:17.890
You don't see the hurry because
you don't have vision, Banner.

04:17.891 --> 04:20.794
Get in the car.
I'll show you some.

04:22.730 --> 04:24.565
[engine starts]

04:29.269 --> 04:31.371
<i>♪ gentle, hopeful music</i>

04:31.372 --> 04:33.507
<i>***</i>

04:35.409 --> 04:37.545
[indistinct chatter]

05:01.735 --> 05:03.337
[exhales]

05:06.273 --> 05:08.376
[Jacob sighs]

05:11.278 --> 05:12.779
It's close enough.

05:12.780 --> 05:14.313
Let's go have a word
with that judge.

05:14.314 --> 05:17.116
Well, you know him, Jake.
That could go two ways.

05:17.117 --> 05:19.118
Well, it could go
two ways out here.

05:19.119 --> 05:21.153
[Jack]
Well, what do you want me to do?

05:21.154 --> 05:24.492
Stay here
and don't start any fights.

05:25.393 --> 05:27.227
We'll be back.

05:35.002 --> 05:36.703
[sighs]

05:36.704 --> 05:38.771
[sniffs]

05:38.772 --> 05:40.006
[knocking]

05:40.007 --> 05:41.508
- Yeah.
- [door opens]

05:41.509 --> 05:42.842
[secretary]
Sheriff McDowell

05:42.843 --> 05:44.444
and Commissioner Dutton
here to see you.

05:44.445 --> 05:46.979
- Show 'em in.
- Yes, sir.

05:46.980 --> 05:49.015
- Gentlemen.
- Thank you.

05:49.016 --> 05:50.583
[Garrett]
Morning, gentlemen.

05:50.584 --> 05:52.018
There's some coffee here
if you want some.

05:52.019 --> 05:53.219
[McDowell]
No, thank you, Roy.

05:53.220 --> 05:54.854
[Jacob]
I'll have some.

05:54.855 --> 05:55.822
[Garrett] Thought gunfighters
didn't drink coffee.

05:55.823 --> 05:57.657
Makes their hand too shaky.

05:57.658 --> 06:00.493
I try not
to shoot at men so far away

06:00.494 --> 06:02.161
that the shake matters.

06:02.162 --> 06:04.431
[chuckles softly] Ca-Can't
ever tell when he's joking.

06:04.432 --> 06:05.832
He's not joking.

06:05.833 --> 06:07.500
What can I do for you?

06:07.501 --> 06:09.703
[McDowell]
<i>People v. Davis.</i>

06:10.738 --> 06:12.505
I don't have that on my docket.

06:12.506 --> 06:14.641
Woman in holding
for miscegenation.

06:14.642 --> 06:19.011
Ah. You mean Asami Ashikaga.

06:19.012 --> 06:22.214
Alice Davis is the falsified
name on the marriage license.

06:22.215 --> 06:24.551
She's married to my wagon boss.

06:24.552 --> 06:26.052
She's not married at all.

06:26.053 --> 06:27.720
State doesn't recognize
their marriage.

06:27.721 --> 06:29.556
[McDowell] They enter a plea
at the arraignment?

06:29.557 --> 06:30.857
[Garrett]
There's no plea.

06:30.858 --> 06:33.526
She was cohabitating
with a Caucasian man.

06:33.527 --> 06:37.229
Has two children with the man
and a marriage license.

06:37.230 --> 06:38.531
She's guilty.

06:38.532 --> 06:40.366
Only thing
to decide is the sentence.

06:40.367 --> 06:41.901
And what did you decide?

06:41.902 --> 06:45.572
It's a quandary, Jake.
Haven't figured it out yet.

06:45.573 --> 06:48.140
If I send the flapper to prison,
then the children stay

06:48.141 --> 06:50.577
in an orphanage
at the state's expense.

06:50.578 --> 06:52.912
And if I deport her, they still
stay at the state's expense

06:52.913 --> 06:55.582
because
those mongrels were born here.

06:55.583 --> 06:57.216
They're U.S. citizens.

06:57.217 --> 06:59.218
Husband is invalid
at the county hospital.

06:59.219 --> 07:01.220
Again, at the state's expense.

07:01.221 --> 07:02.689
Well, I can solve your quandary.

07:02.690 --> 07:07.594
Why don't you just remit them
to my custody?

07:07.595 --> 07:09.128
All of 'em.

07:09.129 --> 07:11.364
Won't cost the state a dime.

07:13.767 --> 07:15.935
- All of them?
- The flapper,

07:15.936 --> 07:18.738
the mongrels,

07:18.739 --> 07:21.775
the invalid, the whole bunch.

07:22.776 --> 07:25.111
What of their flophouse in town?

07:25.112 --> 07:27.079
They'll live at the ranch.

07:27.080 --> 07:29.448
And stay there? Yes?

07:29.449 --> 07:32.385
I'm quite sure
they've had their fill of town.

07:33.654 --> 07:36.122
[clears throat] In that case,
they'll be sentenced

07:36.123 --> 07:39.425
to supervised probation
in your custody.

07:39.426 --> 07:41.093
To be seen in public

07:41.094 --> 07:43.663
in the county together is
a violation of their probation

07:43.664 --> 07:45.498
and will result
in their immediate transfer

07:45.499 --> 07:47.433
- to the county jail.
- Understood.

07:47.434 --> 07:50.637
Provided they identify the
offending priest to the court.

07:50.638 --> 07:52.972
The signature is
conveniently illegible.

07:52.973 --> 07:55.975
Well, it sounds like
you need a handwriting expert.

07:55.976 --> 07:58.912
Can't release her
till I have his identity.

08:01.982 --> 08:04.585
You've known me
for a long time, Roy.

08:06.620 --> 08:09.623
This is about as far
as I care to be pushed.

08:13.260 --> 08:14.927
Threatening a judge, Jake?

08:14.928 --> 08:18.330
Threats have a level
of uncertainty

08:18.331 --> 08:19.966
that comes with them.

08:19.967 --> 08:22.602
I don't make the laws
of this land.

08:22.603 --> 08:25.638
I preside over the consequences
of their violation.

08:25.639 --> 08:28.641
You're married to a Crow woman.

08:28.642 --> 08:31.210
Two states over,
that law applies to you,

08:31.211 --> 08:33.479
and you're the one being judged.

08:33.480 --> 08:35.548
Guess it's a good thing
I live in Montana.

08:35.549 --> 08:36.850
[scoffs softly]

08:46.026 --> 08:48.228
[sniffs]
Oh, my.

08:50.363 --> 08:51.832
[sniffs]

08:54.602 --> 08:57.204
Put that back.

08:58.538 --> 09:00.039
[chuckles]

09:00.040 --> 09:03.009
[Jacob] We'll tell you the name
of the preacher

09:03.010 --> 09:05.613
when you give us the name
of your liquor contact.

09:06.680 --> 09:07.715
How does that sound?

09:09.282 --> 09:12.652
You know, Roy, maybe we ought
to wander on over to my office

09:12.653 --> 09:17.023
and... have a little chat
about this.

09:17.024 --> 09:18.891
This is blackmail.

09:18.892 --> 09:20.027
Hmm.

09:24.765 --> 09:26.800
What do I care
about some mongrel family?

09:45.352 --> 09:47.253
You think you won something?

09:47.254 --> 09:49.055
You haven't won a thing.

09:49.056 --> 09:52.960
There ain't no winner
among us on this deal, Roy.

09:54.695 --> 09:57.097
Not one.

09:58.766 --> 10:00.267
[door closes]

10:04.137 --> 10:07.073
<i>♪ majestic orchestral music</i>

10:07.074 --> 10:09.176
<i>***</i>

10:39.139 --> 10:41.508
<i>***</i>

11:04.131 --> 11:06.199
<i>***</i>

11:16.043 --> 11:18.111
[wind howling]

11:21.749 --> 11:23.917
[shivering breaths]

11:35.395 --> 11:37.329
<i>♪ intriguing music</i>

11:37.330 --> 11:39.366
<i>***</i>

11:40.901 --> 11:43.170
[gasping softly]

11:46.807 --> 11:49.142
[animal snarling]

11:50.944 --> 11:53.580
[growling]

11:59.386 --> 12:02.188
[barking]

12:02.189 --> 12:04.858
[Elizabeth grunting]

12:10.230 --> 12:11.397
[growling]

12:11.398 --> 12:13.699
<i>♪ intense music</i>

12:13.700 --> 12:15.534
<i>***</i>

12:15.535 --> 12:16.536
[screams]

12:17.805 --> 12:20.406
[growling]

12:20.407 --> 12:23.009
[grunts]

12:23.010 --> 12:25.111
[barking]

12:25.112 --> 12:27.713
[panting]
No! No!

12:27.714 --> 12:29.115
[growling]

12:29.116 --> 12:30.883
- [gunshot]
- [whimpers]

12:30.884 --> 12:33.520
[gasping]

12:37.257 --> 12:39.191
Damn things are everywhere
this winter.

12:39.192 --> 12:40.559
He get you good?

12:40.560 --> 12:43.129
People shouldn't be here
in the winter!

12:43.130 --> 12:45.064
Most ain't. The livestock
don't feed themselves.

12:45.065 --> 12:46.934
[panting]

12:49.269 --> 12:51.103
The only thing getting fed
around here is the wolves.

12:51.104 --> 12:53.907
Let me grab you a buggy.
I'll get you to the house.

12:55.843 --> 12:57.544
[pained grunt]

13:10.657 --> 13:12.591
<i>♪ ominous music</i>

13:12.592 --> 13:15.127
<i>***</i>

13:15.128 --> 13:16.796
[hinge creaks]

13:18.131 --> 13:19.933
[sighs]

13:24.304 --> 13:25.637
[chuckles]

13:25.638 --> 13:28.008
Wishful thinking.

13:32.880 --> 13:35.948
An icebox in the house.

13:35.949 --> 13:37.783
[chuckles]

13:37.784 --> 13:40.120
What a day that will be.

13:42.722 --> 13:43.857
[knife clatters]

14:11.384 --> 14:12.952
- What happened?
- Wolf bit her.

14:12.953 --> 14:15.187
He was in the chicken coop.

14:15.188 --> 14:16.855
Let's get her inside.

14:16.856 --> 14:18.892
Go.

14:25.532 --> 14:29.835
Spade, run. Fetch Dr. Miller.

14:29.836 --> 14:31.103
It's not that bad.

14:31.104 --> 14:33.305
A wolf moving about folks
during the day

14:33.306 --> 14:34.806
is either wounded or rabid.

14:34.807 --> 14:36.342
He didn't move
like he was wounded.

14:36.343 --> 14:37.977
Killed every chicken we got.

14:37.978 --> 14:39.678
[Cara] What are you doing
still standing here?

14:39.679 --> 14:41.680
If the thing is rabid,
you're racing time.

14:41.681 --> 14:44.183
Storm's coming, ma'am.
It looks to be a bad one.

14:44.184 --> 14:45.953
All the more reason to hurry.

14:49.957 --> 14:52.059
Let's have a look at it.

14:53.393 --> 14:55.894
- [hisses]
- Does it hurt?

14:55.895 --> 14:58.530
Mm-hmm. Hurts when you do that.

14:58.531 --> 15:00.000
Here.

15:02.035 --> 15:03.869
Here.

15:03.870 --> 15:05.204
[Elizabeth whimpers]

15:05.205 --> 15:08.240
[groans softly]
That hurts.

15:08.241 --> 15:10.176
I swear, girl.

15:10.177 --> 15:13.045
Mother of God,
if it weren't for bad luck,

15:13.046 --> 15:14.913
you'd have none at all.

15:14.914 --> 15:18.084
I suppose the good Lord decided
giving you that face

15:18.085 --> 15:20.419
was all the favors
you were getting. [chuckles]

15:20.420 --> 15:22.254
He can have the face back
if it keeps me

15:22.255 --> 15:25.057
from getting shot at
and bit by wolves,

15:25.058 --> 15:27.093
everything else
He's thrown at me.

15:27.094 --> 15:31.031
I think that face
is worth the trouble, darling.

15:33.400 --> 15:34.834
[groans]

15:35.768 --> 15:37.736
<i>♪ gentle orchestral music</i>

15:37.737 --> 15:39.906
<i>***</i>

16:00.160 --> 16:02.794
Oh. Uh, apologies, sir.

16:02.795 --> 16:05.764
Uh, w-we were told
it's okay, um...

16:05.765 --> 16:07.667
- We meant no harm.
- Explain it to me.

16:09.636 --> 16:12.338
Skiing. Explain it.

16:12.339 --> 16:13.772
Oh, um...

16:13.773 --> 16:16.408
W-We, uh, we learned
in-in the army.

16:16.409 --> 16:18.244
[sighs]

16:18.245 --> 16:20.279
How do you do it?

16:20.280 --> 16:22.814
Oh. Oh, well, um...

16:22.815 --> 16:24.951
<i>[speaking Norwegian]</i>

16:27.287 --> 16:30.322
You stand and, uh, lean forward,
you bend at the knee.

16:30.323 --> 16:33.125
Then you control your speed
by going side to side.

16:33.126 --> 16:36.896
Keep the uphill edge of your ski
into the snow.

16:37.930 --> 16:40.499
It's the closest thing to flying
a man can feel.

16:40.500 --> 16:42.000
Is it difficult to learn?

16:42.001 --> 16:45.037
You spend the first couple
of days, uh, on your ass,

16:45.038 --> 16:48.874
but... after that, it's...

16:48.875 --> 16:50.309
Our body figures out
the motion,

16:50.310 --> 16:52.944
and it's easy, it's like
riding a horse or a bike.

16:52.945 --> 16:54.846
But I can teach you,
if you want.

16:54.847 --> 16:59.518
I don't have the patience for
two days on my ass, thank you.

16:59.519 --> 17:01.987
Can children learn it?

17:01.988 --> 17:03.689
Oh, children pick it up
the quickest.

17:03.690 --> 17:06.492
I think, um, I think
most everyone can do it.

17:06.493 --> 17:08.261
My grandma does it.

17:09.329 --> 17:11.863
Well...
[grunts]

17:11.864 --> 17:16.001
...if you change your mind, sir,
I'm, I'm happy to teach you.

17:16.002 --> 17:17.070
<i>[speaks Norwegian]</i>

17:29.382 --> 17:32.218
Seems a silly way
to waste the day to me.

17:32.219 --> 17:34.553
Does it now?

17:34.554 --> 17:36.856
How many gunfights you been in?

17:38.358 --> 17:39.358
My fair share.

17:39.359 --> 17:42.027
How many bar fights?

17:42.028 --> 17:43.662
More than I can count.

17:43.663 --> 17:47.234
And after, how did you feel?

17:49.169 --> 17:51.737
Alive, which was the goal.

17:51.738 --> 17:54.106
But you liked it.

17:54.107 --> 17:56.108
Tell the truth.

17:56.109 --> 17:58.444
You liked the danger of it.

17:58.445 --> 18:01.380
It gets your blood up, aye.

18:01.381 --> 18:03.915
Aye.

18:03.916 --> 18:06.718
Well, your rancher aside,

18:06.719 --> 18:09.087
it's a rich man's world now.

18:09.088 --> 18:11.290
And everyone gets a taste.

18:11.291 --> 18:15.227
The paper man,
the tradesman, the car salesman,

18:15.228 --> 18:17.062
the doctor, the lawyer.

18:17.063 --> 18:20.266
The one thing
you cannot buy in a store

18:20.267 --> 18:23.569
is the euphoria of peril,

18:23.570 --> 18:28.175
the exhilaration of danger.

18:32.512 --> 18:35.081
I can sell that.

18:35.982 --> 18:38.950
For a fortune.

18:38.951 --> 18:40.919
<i>♪ sweeping orchestral music</i>

18:40.920 --> 18:43.856
<i>***</i>

18:47.827 --> 18:49.929
Whoa, whoa.

18:52.432 --> 18:55.133
Not sure we can beat this
back to the ranch.

18:55.134 --> 18:58.170
Well, I don't want to risk
another night in town.

18:58.171 --> 19:01.273
I'll take my chances
on the storm.

19:01.274 --> 19:03.108
Should have brought
the covered wagon.

19:03.109 --> 19:05.277
It's gonna be a hard trip
on Alice and the kids.

19:05.278 --> 19:06.578
After what they've been through,

19:06.579 --> 19:09.916
I'm sure they won't mind
the trip one little bit.

19:28.535 --> 19:30.469
<i>♪ sorrowful music</i>

19:30.470 --> 19:33.039
<i>***</i>

19:33.940 --> 19:37.910
Zane, we're taking
your family home.

19:39.846 --> 19:43.350
They've been released. You, too.

19:44.651 --> 19:46.318
A bed's my only future.

19:46.319 --> 19:48.554
I can't stand for more
than a minute

19:48.555 --> 19:50.656
before God sticks
a knife in my brain

19:50.657 --> 19:52.057
and I'm throwing up my guts.

19:52.058 --> 19:54.860
They have anybody
to look you over?

19:54.861 --> 19:57.162
Doctor, surgeon? Anybody?

19:57.163 --> 19:59.098
They ain't had no one
look me over.

20:00.333 --> 20:03.336
Well, we'll get you out of here.

20:05.071 --> 20:06.539
I can't walk.

20:09.542 --> 20:11.910
Go to the sheriff
and get the family.

20:11.911 --> 20:14.846
Come on back here,
we'll load up Zane and...

20:14.847 --> 20:16.348
get him home.

20:16.349 --> 20:18.884
We'll get you fixed up
in no time.

20:18.885 --> 20:20.353
You'll see.

20:23.356 --> 20:24.924
[sighs]

20:30.663 --> 20:33.365
Town's always left us alone.

20:33.366 --> 20:35.535
Don't know why they care now.

20:39.306 --> 20:42.107
'Cause Whitfield
told 'em to care.

20:42.108 --> 20:45.243
Chopping us down one by one.

20:45.244 --> 20:47.213
Come spring...

20:48.915 --> 20:52.218
...gonna do some chopping
of our own.

20:53.185 --> 20:55.254
If there's any of us left.

21:01.461 --> 21:03.395
<i>♪ pastoral music</i>

21:03.396 --> 21:05.532
<i>***</i>

21:14.607 --> 21:17.075
It must have been
quite the hunt you were on.

21:17.076 --> 21:18.944
Took all night.

21:18.945 --> 21:21.348
I don't see any meat.

21:24.551 --> 21:26.117
We fell asleep by the river.

21:26.118 --> 21:27.586
<i>[Runs His Horse groans,
speaks Crow]</i>

21:27.587 --> 21:30.155
I hate it when that happens.

21:30.156 --> 21:34.226
We ran into a cowboy yesterday.
Thought it was best to stay put.

21:38.230 --> 21:39.598
A cowboy?

21:39.599 --> 21:41.633
[Pete]
Looking for strays.

21:41.634 --> 21:43.735
He said this isn't a rez.
It's a ranch.

21:43.736 --> 21:46.572
This is where Quanah Parker

21:46.573 --> 21:49.509
lost the cavalry every time
they chased him.

21:50.543 --> 21:52.277
Right here.

21:52.278 --> 21:54.513
This is his homeland.

21:54.514 --> 21:55.947
Ain't his homeland anymore.

21:55.948 --> 21:57.916
Cowboy said Quanah's people

21:57.917 --> 22:00.018
moved a hundred miles north
and to the east.

22:00.019 --> 22:03.154
He didn't seem to mind
we was here.

22:03.155 --> 22:04.424
He said we was welcome.

22:05.392 --> 22:07.660
Cowboys don't own land.

22:08.995 --> 22:11.398
Ranchers own land.

22:14.501 --> 22:16.603
I doubt this rancher
would welcome us.

22:17.970 --> 22:19.304
We should move.

22:19.305 --> 22:20.639
I like it here.

22:20.640 --> 22:22.308
We should move.

22:23.876 --> 22:25.477
What makes
the Comanche reservation

22:25.478 --> 22:27.312
any different than ours?

22:27.313 --> 22:29.416
They got schools there, too.

22:30.450 --> 22:34.020
And priests.
And police.

22:35.422 --> 22:37.789
Maybe we take our chances
with the cowboys.

22:37.790 --> 22:39.858
Maybe we help them
look for strays

22:39.859 --> 22:41.493
in exchange for staying.

22:41.494 --> 22:43.629
One man looking
has bad odds of finding any.

22:43.630 --> 22:45.898
[sighs]
Maybe.

22:48.234 --> 22:49.436
Maybe.

22:53.673 --> 22:55.908
I'll pick up
his tracks on the river.

23:00.780 --> 23:02.549
I'll find his camp.

23:04.250 --> 23:06.552
And I'll see
if I can find his rancher.

23:06.553 --> 23:08.520
<i>♪ mysterious music</i>

23:08.521 --> 23:09.722
<i>***</i>

23:11.658 --> 23:14.661
Stay hidden until I get back.

23:22.469 --> 23:24.604
<i>♪ pulsing, dramatic music ♪</i>

23:35.081 --> 23:37.149
<i>***</i>

23:59.005 --> 24:00.305
- Yes.
- [door opens]

24:00.306 --> 24:01.574
Understood.

24:02.675 --> 24:04.811
I-I'll let the marshal know.
Thank you.

24:06.579 --> 24:08.747
Uh, can I help you, gentlemen?

24:08.748 --> 24:10.649
Marshal Kent.
I need to speak with the marshal

24:10.650 --> 24:11.651
assigned to this post.

24:13.820 --> 24:15.221
One moment.

24:17.557 --> 24:18.991
[door opens]

24:21.427 --> 24:22.862
Follow me, please.

24:36.909 --> 24:39.011
Have a seat, gentlemen.

24:41.247 --> 24:43.348
Where are you in from?

24:43.349 --> 24:44.616
Montana.

24:44.617 --> 24:46.518
It's a long way from home.

24:46.519 --> 24:48.988
Montana is my post.
It is not my home.

24:50.022 --> 24:52.490
Is there a marshal present
who does fieldwork?

24:52.491 --> 24:55.160
Just the one you're looking at.

24:55.161 --> 24:57.863
You patrol this territory,

24:57.864 --> 24:59.731
serving warrants,
making arrests?

24:59.732 --> 25:02.200
Why do I find that
hard to believe?

25:02.201 --> 25:03.669
'Cause you're a bigot

25:03.670 --> 25:06.606
living in the wrong century,
Marshal.

25:07.574 --> 25:09.374
I doubt you traveled
from Montana to question

25:09.375 --> 25:12.177
my ability to serve this badge.

25:12.178 --> 25:13.712
You need something.

25:13.713 --> 25:15.847
And if you have any hopes
of getting it,

25:15.848 --> 25:18.516
you'll ask for it now, before
I throw you out of my office.

25:18.517 --> 25:20.552
You mind that mouth,
woman, before--

25:20.553 --> 25:22.754
Mademoiselle.

25:22.755 --> 25:24.489
We seek

25:24.490 --> 25:27.392
a murderer
who we believe has fled

25:27.393 --> 25:29.128
to the Comanche Nation.

25:33.900 --> 25:34.801
Which one?

25:38.571 --> 25:39.871
Murder?

25:39.872 --> 25:41.808
[Renaud]
Mm-hmm. At least five.

25:43.075 --> 25:45.511
- [Mamie] Quite the savage.
- [Renaud] Two nuns...

25:46.579 --> 25:47.879
...and three priests.

25:47.880 --> 25:48.980
Seems hard to believe,
looking at her.

25:48.981 --> 25:49.915
[Kent]
The child's guilt

25:49.916 --> 25:51.216
is not in question.

25:51.217 --> 25:52.851
She stabbed the nuns

25:52.852 --> 25:54.385
in their sleep.
She shotgunned the priests

25:54.386 --> 25:55.755
when she joined up
with her gang.

25:56.756 --> 25:58.556
- Gang?
- [Thomas] Renegades

25:58.557 --> 26:00.960
from the Crow Agency.

26:07.333 --> 26:10.736
You take this to Esther
in the front.

26:10.737 --> 26:12.437
She's an accomplished
sketch artist.

26:12.438 --> 26:13.639
We can print your posters.

26:13.640 --> 26:15.274
We'll start putting 'em out.

26:16.275 --> 26:19.645
Comanche only respect that badge
if it respects them back.

26:19.646 --> 26:21.747
Many a marshal's found their way

26:21.748 --> 26:24.449
into a pine box
learning that lesson.

26:24.450 --> 26:26.918
Tread lightly, Marshal.

26:26.919 --> 26:28.921
This is not Montana.

26:30.657 --> 26:31.858
Clearly.

26:35.361 --> 26:37.496
[door opens]

26:38.597 --> 26:40.598
[door closes]

26:40.599 --> 26:42.568
I need a sketch of this girl.

26:47.807 --> 26:49.374
This one.

26:49.375 --> 26:51.743
<i>♪ dramatic music</i>

26:51.744 --> 26:54.313
<i>***</i>

27:22.374 --> 27:24.309
<i>♪ soaring music</i>

27:24.310 --> 27:26.478
<i>***</i>

27:44.463 --> 27:45.897
<i>[speaks Italian]</i>

27:45.898 --> 27:47.900
We must carry these ashore.

28:11.057 --> 28:12.224
Load these on the dolly.

28:14.927 --> 28:16.661
Take these.

28:16.662 --> 28:18.430
Come with us.

28:36.415 --> 28:38.183
<i>[jazz band warming up softly]</i>

28:38.184 --> 28:40.218
<i>***</i>

28:40.219 --> 28:41.653
[indistinct chatter]

28:56.235 --> 28:57.303
<i>Cugino.</i>

28:59.772 --> 29:02.407
<i>[Maceo and Luca
speaking Italian]</i>

29:02.408 --> 29:03.975
[kissing]

29:03.976 --> 29:06.012
<i>[Italian conversation continues]</i>

29:17.089 --> 29:18.791
Okay.

29:19.926 --> 29:21.827
Luca says, uh,
you like to fight.

29:21.828 --> 29:23.695
I wouldn't say that.

29:25.865 --> 29:27.265
What would you say, then?

29:27.266 --> 29:28.934
I guess I'd say

29:28.935 --> 29:31.703
I keep running into people
looking for trouble.

29:32.638 --> 29:34.139
And they all think
trouble is me.

29:34.140 --> 29:36.274
[soft chuckle]

29:36.275 --> 29:38.510
I suffer the same predicament.

29:39.478 --> 29:41.212
But he also say
you saved his life.

29:41.213 --> 29:42.613
Yeah, well,

29:42.614 --> 29:44.015
he ran into one of those people.

29:44.016 --> 29:45.150
Know what I mean?

29:45.151 --> 29:47.318
Everywhere, those people.

29:47.319 --> 29:49.787
Yes, they are.

29:49.788 --> 29:52.057
[exhales]

29:52.058 --> 29:53.825
You did a good thing.

29:53.826 --> 29:54.826
He was worth saving.

29:54.827 --> 29:58.629
Tonight we celebrate you.

29:58.630 --> 30:00.765
<i>[speaking Italian]</i>

30:00.766 --> 30:02.033
<i>Sì, signore.</i>

30:02.034 --> 30:03.001
Hungry?

30:03.002 --> 30:04.970
I could eat.

30:04.971 --> 30:06.004
With me.

30:06.005 --> 30:07.438
When he's done eating,

30:07.439 --> 30:08.840
take him to the Galvez.

30:08.841 --> 30:11.410
<i>[chatter in Italian]</i>

30:12.711 --> 30:14.745
<i>[opera playing faintly]</i>

30:14.746 --> 30:16.849
[lively chatter]

30:32.899 --> 30:34.166
What is that?

30:36.903 --> 30:37.970
Mm.

30:44.210 --> 30:45.311
Mm-hmm.

30:46.946 --> 30:49.215
Oh, no, no, no, no. Mm.

30:53.052 --> 30:54.420
Capisce?

31:05.131 --> 31:06.232
Mmm.

31:13.239 --> 31:15.106
I need a telegraph office.

31:15.107 --> 31:16.107
Hotel has phones.

31:16.108 --> 31:18.709
Phone won't do me any good.

31:18.710 --> 31:20.211
I need a telegraph office.

31:20.212 --> 31:22.280
You can send a wire
from the hotel.

31:22.281 --> 31:23.848
I'm ready.

31:23.849 --> 31:26.584
Finish your meal.
There is no rush.

31:26.585 --> 31:28.519
There's no rush for you.

31:28.520 --> 31:30.089
For me everything's a rush.

31:31.890 --> 31:33.024
Andiamo.

31:33.025 --> 31:35.026
<i>♪ optimistic music</i>

31:35.027 --> 31:37.163
<i>***</i>

31:52.111 --> 31:53.712
Thank you.

32:02.021 --> 32:04.390
- Where's the train station?
- Mainland.

32:05.958 --> 32:07.292
How far is the walk?

32:07.293 --> 32:09.827
Signore Maceo said
to escort you to the room

32:09.828 --> 32:11.229
and then to the Hollywood.

32:11.230 --> 32:12.998
When Signore Maceo
asks you to do something,

32:12.999 --> 32:14.966
you must do exactly
the thing that he asks.

32:14.967 --> 32:18.136
I already ate.
I don't need another meal.

32:18.137 --> 32:20.638
You had lunch.
The Hollywood is for dinner.

32:20.639 --> 32:24.109
Signore Maceo is showing you
great hospitality.

32:24.110 --> 32:26.212
To refuse him is an insult.

32:35.421 --> 32:36.454
[blows landing]

32:36.455 --> 32:39.190
[grunting]

32:39.191 --> 32:41.126
<i>♪ suspenseful music ♪</i>

32:41.127 --> 32:43.095
<i>***</i>

33:02.281 --> 33:04.083
<i>***</i>

33:26.238 --> 33:28.240
[tires screech]

33:33.712 --> 33:35.781
[gun clicking empty]

33:42.221 --> 33:44.090
You're lucky he wants you alive.

33:45.391 --> 33:47.793
[grunting]

33:53.232 --> 33:55.534
[train whistle blowing]

33:59.905 --> 34:01.973
[coughing]

34:09.381 --> 34:11.283
[grunts]

34:12.251 --> 34:14.752
Who's looking
for trouble now, hmm?

34:14.753 --> 34:16.554
I gave you food,

34:16.555 --> 34:20.191
the finest suite
in the finest hotel in the city.

34:20.192 --> 34:22.527
Had planned for you
a splendid night

34:22.528 --> 34:25.396
only to show you gratitude.

34:25.397 --> 34:27.732
Look how you repay
my hospitality.

34:27.733 --> 34:31.269
I never asked for it
and I don't want it.

34:31.270 --> 34:33.938
I am needed in Montana.

34:33.939 --> 34:36.607
My family is in danger.

34:36.608 --> 34:38.743
My wife is lost to me.

34:38.744 --> 34:41.379
And I don't have time
for hospitality.

34:41.380 --> 34:42.947
Yes.

34:42.948 --> 34:44.582
The lion hunter
who leaves Africa

34:44.583 --> 34:47.286
for America to hunt men instead.

34:48.287 --> 34:50.121
For your family, huh?

34:50.122 --> 34:51.389
That's what Luca says.

34:51.390 --> 34:52.957
It's a war over land.

34:52.958 --> 34:54.292
My family's land.

34:54.293 --> 34:55.661
And they're losing it.

34:57.363 --> 34:59.330
I know that war.

34:59.331 --> 35:01.667
My family already lost it.

35:05.304 --> 35:07.206
Still we have a problem,
you and me.

35:08.474 --> 35:09.607
You showed me disrespect.

35:09.608 --> 35:11.809
And disrespect is contagious

35:11.810 --> 35:13.611
if not dealt in the moment
it appears.

35:13.612 --> 35:15.280
[sighs]

35:15.281 --> 35:16.882
So you must go away.

35:17.816 --> 35:19.650
Seems that you wish that anyway.

35:19.651 --> 35:21.986
<i>[Maceo speaks Italian]</i>

35:21.987 --> 35:23.222
<i>[Angelo speaks Italian]</i>

35:24.790 --> 35:26.892
<i>[speaks Italian]</i>

35:28.460 --> 35:30.795
Angelo seemed to be

35:30.796 --> 35:32.463
worried about trusting you.

35:32.464 --> 35:34.365
- [chuckles]
- If I was Angelo,

35:34.366 --> 35:35.633
I wouldn't trust you either,

35:35.634 --> 35:37.636
judging by his face.

35:40.306 --> 35:44.074
But a man with a cause
can always be trusted

35:44.075 --> 35:47.179
to do the very thing
that helps his cause.

35:48.113 --> 35:50.316
I'm going to give
that thing to you.

35:51.383 --> 35:54.253
You think you have time
to discuss that?

35:56.955 --> 35:58.857
Yeah, I got time for that.

36:00.158 --> 36:02.126
<i>♪ majestic orchestral music</i>

36:02.127 --> 36:04.363
<i>***</i>

36:16.742 --> 36:18.377
[horse whinnies]

36:22.214 --> 36:24.149
I can't see a thing!

36:29.255 --> 36:31.256
Take it to the pines!

36:31.257 --> 36:33.459
Get moving, boys.

36:44.169 --> 36:46.037
Whoa.

36:57.716 --> 36:59.717
We gonna picket the horses?

36:59.718 --> 37:01.987
Asses to the wind.

37:05.424 --> 37:07.493
We got to flip the wagon!

37:26.778 --> 37:28.847
<i>***</i>

37:47.599 --> 37:48.566
Ready?

37:48.567 --> 37:49.967
Get under it.

37:49.968 --> 37:51.370
[all grunting]

38:12.491 --> 38:14.326
Get everybody under the wagon.

38:33.779 --> 38:36.947
They're gonna be froze to death
by the time this storm passes.

38:36.948 --> 38:38.583
Zane's family can't
make the walk.

38:38.584 --> 38:39.817
Neither can Zane.

38:39.818 --> 38:41.419
I worry
they're walking either way.

38:41.420 --> 38:43.654
They'll just go to lower ground
to get out of this.

38:43.655 --> 38:44.855
We'll just follow their tracks.

38:44.856 --> 38:47.058
What tracks?

39:01.407 --> 39:03.641
[horse neighs]

39:03.642 --> 39:05.711
[grunts]

39:11.517 --> 39:14.052
<i>***</i>

39:36.107 --> 39:39.343
Okay, here's where we all

39:39.344 --> 39:41.378
get to know each other
real good.

39:41.379 --> 39:44.516
Snuggle up,
shoulder to shoulder.

39:49.187 --> 39:51.289
<i>***</i>

40:09.541 --> 40:11.309
[clattering]

40:13.278 --> 40:15.580
[shivering breaths]

40:15.581 --> 40:18.749
Apologies for tracking in
half the storm, Cara.

40:18.750 --> 40:21.587
Snow on the floor
doesn't concern me, Dr. Miller.

40:25.156 --> 40:26.123
Hi.

40:26.124 --> 40:29.027
Ooh. [exhales]

40:30.095 --> 40:31.929
- Got you pretty good.
- Ah! Yeah.

40:31.930 --> 40:33.831
I worry the wolf was rabid,

40:33.832 --> 40:37.301
was moving about during the day.
No fear of man.

40:37.302 --> 40:39.436
More likely a young wolf run off
from the pack and starving,

40:39.437 --> 40:42.574
but, um, we'll take no chances.

40:44.510 --> 40:45.610
Wh-Where does that go?

40:45.611 --> 40:47.479
Well, it goes
right in your belly.

40:48.647 --> 40:50.516
We need to do this 12 times
over the next ten days.

40:51.517 --> 40:53.618
I'm afraid this storm
has made us houseguests

40:53.619 --> 40:55.152
for the evening, Mrs. Dutton, so

40:55.153 --> 40:56.954
I'll give her another shot
in the morning

40:56.955 --> 40:59.657
and leave you with a vaccine
to administer the next ten.

40:59.658 --> 41:01.325
Now, if you'll lift
your dress, please.

41:01.326 --> 41:03.594
No, no, you're not
putting that in my stomach.

41:03.595 --> 41:05.229
I'll take my chances
with the rabies.

41:05.230 --> 41:06.664
There are no chances
with rabies.

41:06.665 --> 41:08.165
It is fatal every time.

41:08.166 --> 41:09.534
But you don't even know
if it was rabid.

41:09.535 --> 41:11.602
It's a chance we can't take.

41:11.603 --> 41:13.804
Uh, I said no.

41:13.805 --> 41:15.172
Hold her.

41:15.173 --> 41:17.341
No! I said...
[gasps]

41:17.342 --> 41:19.209
Let go of me! No!

41:19.210 --> 41:20.845
No! Stop!

41:20.846 --> 41:23.648
- I said no!
- Spade...

41:23.649 --> 41:24.849
- Let go of me!
- Sorry, ma'am.

41:24.850 --> 41:26.717
It's for your own good.

41:26.718 --> 41:28.485
Let go of my legs!

41:28.486 --> 41:30.454
No! No!

41:30.455 --> 41:32.156
No. No.

41:32.157 --> 41:33.824
I said no.

41:33.825 --> 41:36.460
- I know it hurts.
- [screams]

41:36.461 --> 41:38.429
[crying]

41:39.698 --> 41:41.532
But it beats the alternative.

41:41.533 --> 41:43.467
<i>♪ dramatic music</i>

41:43.468 --> 41:44.969
<i>***</i>

41:44.970 --> 41:47.706
[panting]

41:54.179 --> 41:56.682
[crying]

42:00.051 --> 42:03.554
I'll get a room made up for you,
Dr. Miller.

42:03.555 --> 42:05.355
Would you mind sharing with me?

42:05.356 --> 42:07.524
Oh, don't trouble yourself.

42:07.525 --> 42:08.726
I'm fine on the sofa.

42:08.727 --> 42:10.861
I'll get some blankets.

42:10.862 --> 42:12.396
Mr. Dutton isn't here?

42:12.397 --> 42:14.031
No, he went to town.

42:14.032 --> 42:15.867
Hope he had the sense
to stay there.

42:16.835 --> 42:18.436
So do I.

42:29.414 --> 42:31.381
[Elizabeth crying]

42:31.382 --> 42:33.383
<i>♪ somber music</i>

42:33.384 --> 42:35.520
<i>***</i>

42:49.901 --> 42:52.770
This is too much.

42:52.771 --> 42:55.305
It's too much.

42:55.306 --> 42:58.709
I love him,
but this isn't living.

42:58.710 --> 43:00.712
This is surviving.

43:02.113 --> 43:03.347
Barely at that.

43:03.348 --> 43:05.917
Winter is always hard.

43:07.786 --> 43:10.054
And this one has been
harder than most.

43:10.055 --> 43:12.757
But then the spring comes.

43:12.758 --> 43:14.625
And there is nothing so splendid

43:14.626 --> 43:17.494
as the mountains in the spring.

43:17.495 --> 43:20.297
Wait. Wait till you see it.

43:20.298 --> 43:23.300
I won't be here to see it.

43:23.301 --> 43:26.738
When the storm passes,
I'm going home.

43:29.941 --> 43:31.542
[crying]

43:42.320 --> 43:44.454
<i>♪ dramatic music</i>

43:44.455 --> 43:46.958
<i>***</i>

43:54.700 --> 43:57.235
<i>[jazz music playing]</i>

44:01.873 --> 44:03.742
Whiskey, if you please.

44:07.345 --> 44:10.314
Leave it to the Scots to ride
out the storm in a saloon.

44:10.315 --> 44:12.983
I don't need some Dutton
seeing us together.

44:12.984 --> 44:14.518
You with that badge
on your chest.

44:14.519 --> 44:17.321
No Duttons in town to see us.

44:17.322 --> 44:19.857
No one in here to see us at all.

44:19.858 --> 44:22.659
Except the bartender.

44:22.660 --> 44:24.763
That memory fades with a tip.

44:26.031 --> 44:27.531
You a religious man?

44:27.532 --> 44:30.167
No less than the next, I guess.

44:30.168 --> 44:32.369
I've called on Him
when I needed.

44:32.370 --> 44:34.604
Still breathing,
so I guess He listened.

44:34.605 --> 44:35.539
You?

44:35.540 --> 44:37.808
I believe...

44:37.809 --> 44:41.880
I'm a sinner who will never see
the gates of heaven.

44:43.114 --> 44:45.650
But I believe they exist.

44:48.887 --> 44:52.356
Whitfield can look at a mountain

44:52.357 --> 44:55.426
and see the gold deep inside it.

44:56.594 --> 44:59.096
He saw those Vikings sliding
down the mountainside

44:59.097 --> 45:02.867
like otters making fools
of themselves...

45:02.868 --> 45:05.369
and he sees a business in it,

45:05.370 --> 45:06.904
sees a fortune in it.

45:06.905 --> 45:08.940
A man of vision.

45:11.376 --> 45:13.211
There's no vision.

45:14.913 --> 45:16.882
He sees through us.

45:18.249 --> 45:20.752
Sees the greed in our hearts.

45:25.423 --> 45:29.226
I've never met a man
who scares me.

45:29.227 --> 45:32.697
Not once in my life, until now.

45:36.634 --> 45:38.837
The man scares me, Clyde.

45:40.772 --> 45:42.840
He fucking scares me to death.

45:42.841 --> 45:45.409
<i>♪ ominous music</i>

45:45.410 --> 45:46.877
[Kent]
"Republicans plan to introduce

45:46.878 --> 45:49.746
the Indian Citizenship Act
to Congress.

45:49.747 --> 45:52.950
The law would grant citizenship
to all Indians

45:52.951 --> 45:56.454
born in the territorial
United States."

45:57.455 --> 45:59.957
Why the fuck would they do that?

45:59.958 --> 46:03.460
It is the inevitable result
of their assimilation.

46:03.461 --> 46:04.529
What?

46:06.064 --> 46:07.431
Well...

46:07.432 --> 46:09.334
[sighs]

46:10.468 --> 46:13.137
...if we wish them to abandon
their pagan ways,

46:13.138 --> 46:15.840
we must offer
the reward of equality.

46:15.841 --> 46:19.776
But you want Indians to vote,
marry our women?

46:19.777 --> 46:23.814
Oh, they're your women,
all of them?

46:23.815 --> 46:26.316
- To choose their own fate--
- Don't feed me your bullshit,

46:26.317 --> 46:29.453
Father, I've seen the graveyard
in your backyard.

46:29.454 --> 46:31.688
I know what you think
of Indians.

46:31.689 --> 46:33.457
You know what I think
of Indians who resist

46:33.458 --> 46:35.360
their own evolution, but...

46:37.028 --> 46:40.130
...to those who accept it
I show only love.

46:40.131 --> 46:41.999
[scoffs]
You don't see the danger in it?

46:42.000 --> 46:44.501
No, I see no danger in it.

46:44.502 --> 46:47.337
So I suppose you'd just let
Black men marry white women.

46:47.338 --> 46:51.909
Well, they do so in France,
and it has caused no calamities.

46:51.910 --> 46:53.878
You can marry
outside your race in France?

46:53.879 --> 46:57.114
Well, the south of France was
ruled by Black men at one time,

46:57.115 --> 46:59.683
as was Spain and Italy.

46:59.684 --> 47:01.785
Black men ruled Europe?

47:01.786 --> 47:04.188
For 800 years.

47:04.189 --> 47:06.356
Part of that empire
still exists today.

47:06.357 --> 47:09.459
It's called Andalusia,

47:09.460 --> 47:13.030
and it truly has
some of the most...

47:13.031 --> 47:15.966
magnificent architecture
in the world.

47:15.967 --> 47:18.036
[marshals laughing]

47:19.704 --> 47:20.871
It's true.

47:20.872 --> 47:23.908
[laughter continues]

47:23.909 --> 47:25.042
[Thomas coughing]

47:25.043 --> 47:26.010
[arrow whooshes]

47:26.011 --> 47:27.145
[grunts]

47:27.845 --> 47:30.180
- Oh, Jesus.
- [Thomas gasping]

47:30.181 --> 47:31.215
- Father!
- What?

47:31.216 --> 47:32.783
Get up, get the fuck up!

47:33.718 --> 47:35.852
[arrows whooshing]

47:35.853 --> 47:37.355
[grunting]

47:38.723 --> 47:40.390
They're gonna try
to draw us out,

47:40.391 --> 47:41.858
and then they'll charge.

47:41.859 --> 47:42.893
We wait until they do.

47:42.894 --> 47:44.728
I am a man of the cloth.

47:44.729 --> 47:46.630
I'd say these sons of bitches
are resisting evolution, Father.

47:46.631 --> 47:48.065
Now take the fucking gun.

47:48.066 --> 47:49.199
- [arrow whooshes]
- Take the fucking gun.

47:49.200 --> 47:51.501
[Natives whooping]

47:51.502 --> 47:53.871
- [arrow whooshes]
- [Renaud panting]

47:57.008 --> 47:59.911
[whooping]

48:04.215 --> 48:06.985
[shouting indistinctly]

48:08.453 --> 48:10.187
Now.

48:10.188 --> 48:12.389
[Natives shouting, whooping]

48:12.390 --> 48:15.426
[Renaud screaming]

48:17.562 --> 48:19.763
- [gun clicking empty]
- [continues screaming]

48:19.764 --> 48:21.365
<i>♪ intense music ♪</i>

48:21.366 --> 48:23.001
<i>***</i>

48:26.571 --> 48:29.607
[Renaud panting]

48:35.813 --> 48:37.747
<i>♪ melancholy music</i>

48:37.748 --> 48:39.917
<i>***</i>

48:50.628 --> 48:52.229
Don't worry, Father.

48:52.230 --> 48:54.931
The penitent man shall pass.

48:54.932 --> 48:56.600
All you got to do...

48:56.601 --> 48:57.968
[grunting]

48:57.969 --> 48:59.504
...is ask for forgiveness.

49:16.154 --> 49:17.755
[passengers screaming]

49:19.457 --> 49:21.325
[Alex]
<i>Dear Spencer,</i>

49:21.326 --> 49:24.095
<i>I have begun my journey
to find you.</i>

49:24.962 --> 49:28.498
<i>To bring you the life
growing inside me,</i>

49:28.499 --> 49:31.135
<i>the child that shall bear
your name.</i>

49:31.136 --> 49:33.637
[hyperventilating]

49:33.638 --> 49:35.605
<i>I thirst for the moment
I look in your eyes</i>

49:35.606 --> 49:37.207
<i>and you pull me close</i>

49:37.208 --> 49:41.145
<i>and we make another and another,</i>

49:41.146 --> 49:43.214
<i>a little army of us.</i>

49:46.417 --> 49:49.287
[screaming]

49:50.655 --> 49:53.290
<i>This is the dream
that fuels me to you.</i>

49:53.291 --> 49:57.194
<i>It is my only thought,
my only desire.</i>

49:57.195 --> 50:01.131
<i>Your eyes upon me,
your arms around me,</i>

50:01.132 --> 50:05.069
<i>and our bodies pressed together
as if they are one.</i>

50:05.070 --> 50:07.205
<i>***</i>

50:10.708 --> 50:12.176
[Luca]
An adventure this will be.

50:12.177 --> 50:13.177
[Maceo]
Stick to the roads

50:13.178 --> 50:14.511
marked on the maps.

50:14.512 --> 50:17.681
Those are the only roads
I control.

50:17.682 --> 50:19.083
Send Luca back on the train.

50:19.084 --> 50:21.718
Truck is yours
if you can make it.

50:21.719 --> 50:24.354
I know what it's like
to lose your home.

50:24.355 --> 50:27.258
Maybe now you can get back
in time to save it.

50:30.928 --> 50:34.132
For the police
who can be bribed.

50:35.900 --> 50:39.203
And for the police... who can't.

50:39.204 --> 50:41.205
Get my whiskey to Fort Worth.

50:41.206 --> 50:43.907
Luca comes back with the money,

50:43.908 --> 50:46.144
we shake hands
next time we meet.

50:50.381 --> 50:52.150
[engine starts]

50:57.722 --> 50:59.689
<i>♪ atmospheric music</i>

50:59.690 --> 51:01.792
<i>***</i>

51:07.965 --> 51:10.368
[wind whooshing]

51:19.444 --> 51:21.479
[clattering]

51:25.750 --> 51:28.153
- [thud]
- [woman screams]

51:35.326 --> 51:37.162
[clattering continues]

51:40.298 --> 51:43.467
<i>♪ eerie music</i>

51:43.468 --> 51:46.304
[clattering]

52:02.887 --> 52:05.022
[wind whistling]

52:06.224 --> 52:09.793
[Elsa] <i>Hell is described
as rivers of fire</i>

52:09.794 --> 52:12.296
<i>and canyons of coal and ash.</i>

52:12.297 --> 52:14.498
<i>Perhaps it is taught that way</i>

52:14.499 --> 52:18.335
<i>because the people of Palestine
and Israel cannot comprehend</i>

52:18.336 --> 52:21.239
<i>the merciless, loveless nature
of cold.</i>

52:22.273 --> 52:25.342
<i>To the mountain people,
hell is a river frozen</i>

52:25.343 --> 52:27.611
<i>with canyon walls of ice</i>

52:27.612 --> 52:31.615
<i>and bitter air that ruptures
lungs and rapes your sanity.</i>

52:31.616 --> 52:35.185
<i>Hell is winter,</i>

52:35.186 --> 52:37.153
<i>and winter is here
to ravage all of us.</i>

52:37.154 --> 52:38.856
[wolf growling]

52:43.328 --> 52:45.363
- [gunshot]
- [Cara screams]

52:50.067 --> 52:52.836
<i>♪ ominous music</i>

52:52.837 --> 52:55.740
<i>***</i>

52:58.543 --> 53:00.810
<i>♪ haunting music</i>

53:00.811 --> 53:10.855
<i>***</i>
